.Sappho's life spanned one of the most exciting periods in Greek history. Green's novel, full of details about daily life on ancient Lesbos, draws the reader into the political and social climate of her world: the civil strife accompanying the transition from aristocracy to mercantilism, the household relations between slave and aristocrat, the details of sea travel in the Aegean. Green wrote the novel while living on Lesbos, and his graceful rendering of the landscape, the rhythms of the seasons, and the varied flora of Sappho's island pervades the narrative.Sappho's poetry reveals a direct, spontaneous woman who eschewed artifice and embellishment. Green's extraordinary talent captures those qualities and brings this woman of unflinching honesty very much to life.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh  aaegean.  aancient greek history.  aancient greek literature.  aancient lesbos.  aancient literature.  aaristocracy.  acivil strife.  acultural history.  adaily life.  aerotic.  afatal affair.  agreek history.  agreek lyric poet.  ahistorical evidence.  ahistorical imagination.  ainsightful.  aintimate.  aisland of lesbos.  alesbos.  alove affair.  ameditations.  amercantilism.  aphaon.  apoems.  apoetry.  apolitical climate.  apolitical history.  asappho.  asea travel.  aself questioning.  asensual.  aslavery.  asocial climate.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz978052020340240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520917156?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520917156423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520917156/original  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press 